[start section id="20103"]

This is a 73-year-old male with history of coronary artery disease status-post MI 19 years ago, status-post CABG 2007 times two vessels.  The patient has history of congestive heart failure, atrial fibrillation, as well as prior history of chronic anticoagulation.  The patient has history of hypertension and insulin-dependent diabetes as well as hyperlipidemia.  The patient had shortness-of-breath two-months ago, and he was found to have microcytic anemic as well as splenic flexure colon cancer.  The patient also was found to have exacerbation of his CHF with increased swelling and increased weight.  They went up on his Lasix because of his exertional shortness-of-breath at that time.  He was not able to walk more than one block.  He had orthopnea.  The patient improved on increasing dose of Lasix as well as iron supplement.  The patient currently has no shortness-of-breath except with extreme exertion.  The patient denies orthopnea.  The patient does not use oxygen.  The patient denies any paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea.  The patient had chest pain at the time within the form of heaviness, but currently, he denies any chest pain.  The patient denies any palpitations.  The patient denies any leg swelling.  The patient lost weight, and he does not feel congested as before.  The patient has history of A-fib for two years on chronic anticoagulation; however, after the discovery of his anemia, they stopped Coumadin about four weeks ago.  His INR today is 1.3.  The patient denies any history of stroke.  The patient has had diabetes for 20 years.  He has been on insulin for one-year.  The patient has history of congestive heart failure.  His last echo was one-year ago in Jumping Branch.  He said that his EF was 37 however no actual report.  He had pleural effusions on-and-off.  The last one was aspirated through thoracentesis about last winter in Jumping Branch.  The patient never smoked.  He has family history of coronary artery disease but no premature atherosclerosis.  The patient does not drink alcohol.  The patient takes his medication on time.  There was no coronary angiogram done after his bypass surgery.  The patient is not aware of any stents done after his bypass surgery as well.

